ypogastric plexus","Sympathetic fibres from T10-L2 via the superior hypogastric plexus","Pudendal nerve from S2-S4","Sympathetic fibres from T10-L2 via the inferior hypogastric plexus","Parasympathetic fibres from S2-S4 via the prostatic plexus"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe corpus cavernosum receives its primary innervation from \u003Cstrong\u003Eparasympathetic fibres from S2-S4 via the prostatic plexus\u003C/strong\u003E. These fibres travel through the cavernous nerves to reach the erectile tissue. \u003Cstrong\u003EParasympathetic fibres from S2-S4 via the superior hypogastric plexus\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Esympathetic fibres from T10-L2 via the superior hypogastric plexus\u003C/strong\u003E do not directly innervate the corpus cavernosum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epudendal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E provides somatic innervation to the external genitalia, including sensation to the penile skin and motor control of the bulbospongiosus and ischiocavernosus muscles, but does not innervate the corpus cavernosum directly. \u003Cstrong\u003ESympathetic fibres from T10-L2 via the inferior hypogastric plexus\u003C/strong\u003E contribute to detumescence but are not the primary innervation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EParasympathetic stimulation causes vasodilation of the helicine arteries and relaxation of the smooth muscle in the corpus cavernosum, leading to erection. Sympathetic stimulation causes vasoconstriction and detumescence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The corpus cavernosum receives parasympathetic innervation from S2-S4 via the prostatic plexus through cavernous nerves","Parasympathetic stimulation causes vasodilation and erection while sympathetic stimulation causes detumescence","The pudendal nerve provides somatic innervation to the external genitalia but not the corpus cavernosum"],"references":["Dean RC, Lue TF. Physiology of penile erection and pathophysiology of erectile dysfunction. Urol Clin North Am. 2005 Nov;32(4):379-95, v. doi: 10.1016/j.ucl.2005.08.007. PMID: 16291031; PMCID: PMC1351051.","Tun\u00e7kol E, Purkart L, Eigen L, Vida I, Brecht M. Fiber counts and architecture of the human dorsal penile nerve. Sci Rep. 2023 May 31;13(1):8862. doi: 10.1038/s41598-023-35030-w. PMID: 37258532; PMCID: PMC10232416.","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press.","Gurung P, Yetiskul E, Jialal I. Physiology, Male Reproductive System. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538429/","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48012"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15781"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48012"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T23:10:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T23:10:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8472"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62565"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt"